<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-676-321  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 676 321.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Dec 10 1990 v7 n49 p87(4)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DBMS contenders run a close race; dBASE IV, Paradox and R:baseeach have distinct strong suits, disadvantages. (Software Review)(overview of three evaluations of leading data base managementsystems)(includes related article on testing methodology)(evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mirecki, Ted.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>The three leading database management systems (DBMSs) on themarket are evaluated and compared.andP;  Ashton-Tate's dBASE IV 1.1,Borland International Inc's Paradox 3.5, and Microrim's R:base 3.1are all available in network versions that offer automatic dataupdating of information changed on a workstation when it ischanged by another user anywhere on the network, query by examplefacilities, and user-configurable screen refreshing.andP;  Each productuses a different implementation of relational DBMS architectureand has its own distinctive programming language.andP;  None appearssignificantly superior to the others; each has strengths andweaknesses.andP;  All three products can produce excellent end-userapplications, leaving the final purchasing decision a matter ofdeveloper preference.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Ashton-Tate (Products)Borland International Inc. (Products)Microrim Inc. (Products).andO;Ticker:    BORL.andO;Product:   dBASE IV 1.1 (Data base management system).andO;Topic:     Data base management systemsEvaluationSoftware packages.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Analyst's scoreboard. (table)Specs. (table)No clear winner among database heavyweights. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Ted MireckiandM;As the networked workstation replaces both the stand-alone PC and themainframe in corporate offices, an application's networking capabilitiesbecome increasingly important.andP;  This is especially true ofdatabase-management systems, where not only the application but the data thesystems manage must be shared among multiple users.andM;PC Week Labs reviewed three major multiuser database products that haverecently been upgraded: Ashton-Tate's dBASE IV version 1.1, BorlandInternational Inc.'s Paradox version 3.5 and Microrim Inc.'s R:base version3.1.andM;These products represent three very different implementations of databasearchitecture and programming language, as well as the balance betweenprogrammed applications and interactive use.andP;  Yet despite their fundamentaldifferences, they share some common features.andM;One such commonality is the automatic update of data displayed on aworkstation when it is changed by another user anywhere on the network.andM;Borland pioneered this feature more than two years ago with Paradox 2.0, anddBASE and R:base have since implemented it in similar fashion.andM;In all three products reviewed, the refresh interval between automaticupdates can be specified, or the refresh can be turned off entirely.andP;  Ifturned off at the workstation, data is still automatically updated if it hasbeen changed between the time of display and the time that a user attempts tochange it.andM;To ensure that such updates do not go unnoticed by the user, users mustacknowledge them with an extra keystroke before proceeding with their ownchanges.andM;Another common feature is the interactive query-by-example (QBE) facility.andO;This was also first implemented in the microcomputer world by Paradox, inversion 1.0, but it is derived from IBM's DB2 mainframe database.andP;  All threeproducts present a virtually identical interface for this function (seephotos, Page 90), and all are functionally similar.andM;None of the three reviewed products was found by PC Week Labs to be markedlysuperior to the others; each has strong points and weak points in areas ofperformance, architecture, programming language and development environment.andM;All are capable of producing high-quality end-user applications for use onnetworks.andP;  The final choice will depend on the developer's preference.andM;</TEXT></DOC>